# Brief: <System / Project Name>

A short statement of what this brief is and what the drafter should produce: a
buildable-system proposal (`proposal.tex`) compiling under XeLaTeX, following the
10-section template, scoring against the 9-dimension rubric, and passing the
mandatory audit (BOM arithmetic + spec/link-budget consistency + sourceability).

State the **hard constraints** up front — the customer's non-negotiables (e.g.
invisibility, no conduit, a bandwidth floor). The reviewer scores constraint
satisfaction (dim 3) on whether the design visibly threads each one through
every section.

## Premise (section 1)

One paragraph: what the system is, what it delivers, and the hard constraints it
satisfies. This becomes the Premise callout — it must be legible without further
reading.

## The Idea (section 2)

Why this approach, and what the conventional answer costs or fails to deliver.
State the value proposition the approver is being asked to fund. (For
`customer_kind: internal`, frame this as a budget justification.)

## Topology (section 3)

The system architecture: the principal structure (hub-and-spoke, mesh,
pipeline) and how its elements connect. Note the capacity limits (port counts,
power budgets, spoke counts) so the auditor can cross-check them against the BOM.

## The Core Subsystem (section 4)

The central engineered element the whole proposal turns on. Subsections for
component selection, the install/method approach, the **delivery capability**
(how the executor acquires the tools/skills/staff to build AND maintain it — the
deliverability anchor), and lifetime/maintenance.

## The Interfaces (section 5)

The secondary engineered layer — how the core connects to the endpoints, with
the part choices matched at both ends. State rated specs (distances, power) so
the auditor can check them against the demand.

## Coverage / Capacity (section 6)

How the system covers its full required scope and the design rule that
guarantees it (e.g. one access point per major room). State the dominant
constraint that drives the rule.

## Bill of Materials (section 7)

The central artifact. State the assumptions the BOM is sized against (zone
count, endpoint count, labor rate). Then enumerate:
- A multi-section priced BOM (Item | Qty | Unit | Total), grouped by subsystem,
  with a Materials subtotal. Every price needs a basis (planning range, vendor
  list price, quote).
- A labor estimate (Task | Hours | Cost) with a Labor subtotal.
- A project total (Materials + Labor → Total).

## Installation / Operating Notes (section 8)

Sequenced execution and operating guidance (build order, per-stage testing,
labeling, power/ventilation/access constraints).

## References / Compliance (section 9 — optional)

Standards and spec sheets cited (e.g. ITU-T G.652D, datasheets). Omit if the
piece cites nothing.

## Open Decisions (section 10)

The unresolved engineering choices, tracked honestly — the choices a
commissioning conversation would need to settle, and what each implies for
cost / scope / deliverability.
